      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Which of the following statements is true regarding the interaction of hemoglobin with 2, 3-BPG</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9882383",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29819,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B)&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Binding of 2,3 BPG decreases the affinity of Hb to O2 and shifts the ODC to right&nbsp;</span></strong></span></span><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Interaction of Hemoglobin with 2, 3 BPG</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>2, 3 BPG</strong> is an <strong>intermediate of Glycolysis</strong> synthesized with the help of <strong>2, 3 BPG Shunt or Rapoport Luebering Cycle. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>Hemoglobin tetramer </strong>binds to <strong>one mol of 2,3 BPG</strong> in the central cavity formed by <strong>four subunits.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>2,3 BPG</strong> forms <strong>salt bridges</strong> with a<strong> terminal amino group of both &beta; globin chain </strong>via, <strong>Valine, Lysine and Histidine.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Binding of <strong>2,3 BPG decreases the affinity of Hb to Oxygen</strong>, by <strong>stabilizing the T state</strong> and shifts the<strong> ODC to right.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>2, 3 BPG</strong> has <strong>decreased interaction with HbF</strong> as histidine forms <strong>salt bridges </strong>with <strong>2,3 BPG is not </strong>present in<strong> &gamma; chain of HbF</strong> &rarr;<strong> Instead</strong> of <strong>Histidine</strong> it is <strong>Serine, so 2,3 BPG </strong>has <strong>less interaction </strong>with <strong>Fetal Hb</strong> &rarr; accounts for <strong>high affinity of HbF</strong> towards <strong>Oxygen.</strong></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/19/picture18.jpg\" style=\"height:277px; width:700px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: 2, 3-BPG is an intermediate of gluconeogenesis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This statement is <strong>incorrect.</strong> <strong>2, 3-BPG </strong>is formed from <strong>1,3-bisphosphoglycerate</strong> during<strong> glycolysis, not gluconeogenesis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Binding of 2,3-BPG stabilizes the R state:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This is<strong> incorrect.</strong> <strong>2, 3-BPG </strong>binds to and stabilizes the <strong>T (tense) state of Hb</strong>,<strong> not</strong> the<strong> R (relaxed) state</strong>, which has a <strong>higher affinity for oxygen.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>2, 3-BPG has increased interaction with HbF:</strong> This is <strong>incorrect</strong>. <strong>HbF</strong> has a <strong>lower affinity for 2, 3-BPG </strong>than <strong>adult hemoglobin</strong> (HbA), which contributes to<strong> its higher affinity for oxygen</strong>, <strong>facilitating oxygen </strong>transfer from the <strong>mother to the fetus.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>2, 3-BPG</strong> is a <strong>metabolite </strong>in the <strong>glycolytic pathway</strong> that binds to <strong>deoxyhemoglobin</strong> (<strong>Hb</strong> in the<strong> T or tense state)</strong> and <strong>stabilizes it</strong>, which <strong>decreases</strong> the <strong>oxygen affinity of Hb</strong>. This <strong>interaction</strong> is crucial for the <strong>release of O2 in tissues. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Binding of <strong>2, 3-BPG to Hb </strong>thus<strong> facilitates the delivery of oxygen</strong> to tissues by <strong>promoting the release of oxygen </strong>from <strong>Hb</strong>, which is reflected as a <strong>rightward shift in the ODC.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 288.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
