      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 65-year-old man comes to the clinic with symptoms including a bluish tint to his skin on his face and extremities, shortness of breath, and headaches. His medical history reveals that he has been taking sulfa drugs. Given these clinical features and medication history, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3664273",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29820,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D)&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Methemoglobinemia</span></strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Hemoglobin</strong> containing heme iron&#39;s <strong>ferric (Fe3+)</strong> state is called <strong>methaemoglobin</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Methemoglobinemia</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - <strong>abnormal</strong> accumulation of <strong>methaemoglobin.</strong> It can be caused by <strong>genetic abnormalities</strong> <strong>(inherited methemoglobinemia)</strong> or intake of certain drugs &amp; chemicals <strong>(acquired methemoglobinemia)</strong> such as <strong>sulphonamides, aniline</strong> etc.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Since <strong>methaemoglobin</strong> has <strong>poor binding capacity with oxygen</strong> results in <strong>bluish discoloration of the skin and mucous</strong> membranes <strong>(cyanosis) </strong>and<strong> </strong>symptoms of<strong> tissue hypoxia</strong> such as <strong>anxiety, headache, dyspnoea, coma and death</strong> can occur. </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Sickle cell anemia: </span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Characterized by<strong> lifelong pain crises,</strong> <strong>chronic hemolytic anemia</strong> with <strong>hyperbilirubinemia</strong> and <strong>increased</strong> susceptibility to <strong>infections</strong>. Other symptoms -<strong> acute chest syndrome, stroke, splenic and renal dysfunction</strong> and <strong>bone changes </strong>due to <strong>marrow hyperplasia.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Carboxy hemoglobinemia:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong> Carbon monoxide </strong>binds to <strong>haemoglobin</strong> very <strong>avidly</strong>. The patient presents with <strong>confusion and</strong> symptoms of<strong> O2 deprivation,</strong> but <strong>not dyspnoea,</strong> since the <strong>hemoglobin is fully saturated, </strong>and <strong>lips</strong> have a typical <strong>red colour</strong> as a result of the <strong>hemoglobin getting oxygenated.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&beta;-Thalassemia:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;Characterized by a <strong>decrease or absence of beta chains synthesis</strong> with <strong>compensatory increase</strong> in<strong> gamma or</strong> <strong>delta chains.</strong> They<strong> present</strong> with<strong> hypochromic microcytic anemia </strong>and <strong>ineffective erythropoiesis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Methemoglobinemia</strong>, associated with certain medications like <strong>sulfa drugs</strong>, leads to symptoms of <strong>cyanosis and dyspnea </strong>due to an <strong>altered oxygen-carrying state of hemoglobin</strong>. <strong>Sickle cell anemia and &beta;-Thalassemia </strong>present with <strong>different hematological issues</strong>, while <strong>carboxyhemoglobinemia </strong>is typically linked to<strong> carbon monoxide exposure</strong>,<strong> not sulfa drugs.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 692-693.</span></span></strong></p>",
