      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 45-year-old male presents to the clinic for a routine health checkup. As part of his evaluation, a blood test is performed. When his blood sample is treated with Ehrlich&rsquo;s solution, it gives a purplish-brown color. Which of the following substances is most likely present in the patient&#39;s blood to account for this color change?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7221832",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29816,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A)&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Urobilinogen</span></strong>&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ehrlich&rsquo;s solution</strong> is a <strong>reagent </strong>used to test for the<strong> presence of urobilinogen</strong> in <strong>urine or blood.</strong> A <strong>positive reaction,</strong> indicated by a <strong>purplish-brown color change</strong>, suggests the <strong>presence of urobilinogen. Urobilinogen</strong> is a <strong>colorless by-product of bilirubin reduction</strong>. It is <strong>formed </strong>in the<strong> intestines</strong> by <strong>bacterial action on bilirubin</strong>, a portion of which is <strong>absorbed</strong> back into the <strong>bloodstream</strong>, <strong>excreted</strong> in the<strong> urine</strong>, or further <strong>converted</strong> into<strong> stercobilin</strong> and <strong>excreted in feces</strong>. The <strong>presence of urobilinogen </strong>in the patient&#39;s blood, indicated by the reaction with<strong> Ehrlich&#39;s reagent</strong>, can be associated with <strong>various liver and hematological disorders</strong>, making it an <strong>important</strong> <strong>diagnostic marker.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><u>Other Options:</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Conjugated bilirubin&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">- This is<strong> water-soluble</strong> and would<strong> not react to Ehrlich&rsquo;s solution</strong> in the same manner as <strong>urobilinogen.</strong> It is typically <strong>excreted into the bile</strong> and helps to<strong> color the feces and urine.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Unconjugated bilirubin</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> - This is<strong> not water-soluble</strong> and is<strong> carried in the bloodstream to the liver</strong>, where it is <strong>conjugated</strong>. It would<strong> not</strong> directly react with <strong>Ehrlich&rsquo;s solution</strong> to produce a <strong>purplish-brown color.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Hemosiderin</strong> - This is an <strong>iron-storage complex </strong>and is<strong> not </strong>typically detected in <strong>blood tests</strong> using <strong>Ehrlich&rsquo;s solution</strong>. It is usually found<strong> within tissues </strong>in conditions of <strong>iron overload.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/19/picture9.jpg\" style=\"height:703px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan, 9/e: page 279, 350</span></strong></span></span></p>",
